Views are perfectly normal Python functions that expect certain arguments. If a request comes in and Django figures out what view function to call, then it will call the function and pass in a request object
Note: You can also make `class` views instead of `function` views. But it's usually a good idea to keep things simple and use functions.

models.py has no reason to know about views.py. The models only care about interacting with the database and giving the database tables extra logic and functionality.

div.font:
Once a view has done all the clever stuff it needs to do, it's last job is to create an HTTP response. Usually this response will contain some HTML. This is where templates come in.
A view will fetch a template and then render it with the correct data.
If a template needs to render a form or something from the database, then it doesn't go and fetch that stuff. It's pretty dumb.
The view is responsible for feeding the template everything it needs through the context dictionary.

Sometimes the rendered HTML will need to know about some urls. This happens if you want your frontend to submit a request (eg an htmx request) or link to a different page.
The template language allows you to make use of the url configuration from within your templates. The template doesn't directly import from urls.py or anything like that. If it needs to know a url then it can call a function to get what it needs
